<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   NATO's Woerner Defends Decision on Bosnian Air Strikes </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    NATO's Woerner Defends Decision on Bosnian Air Strikes </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1104195694 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1849 GMT 11 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1104195694 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cologne (DDP/ADN) -- NATO Secretary General Manfred 
Woerner has strongly defended the alliance's air strike against 
Serb positions near Gorazde. "I cherish the hope that the new 
determination that can be seen in the United Nations and in us 
will not fail to have the appropriate effect on the Serbs," 
Woerner said on the Cologne private television station RTL on 
Monday evening [11 April]. He expressed the expectation that 
this would push the peace process on further, "If possible at 
the negotiating table." 
  With regard to Russian criticism, Woerner added that one 
could not start hours of consultation in the Security Council 
"to realize after days that we should really have taken action, 
but it was unfortunately impossible and now the people are 
already dead." The current consultation mechanism "should also 
satisfy Russian requirements." The NATO secretary general 
pointed out that the UN resolution under which the alliance was 
acting was "fully supported by Russia." 

</TEXT>

