<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Italian Air Base Reportedly Refuses To Service NATO Planes </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Italian Air Base Reportedly Refuses To Service NATO Planes </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1204101894 Belgrade TANJUG in English 0953 GMT 12 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1204101894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Udine, April 12 (TANJUG)--The technical bureau of 
the Italian military airport in Aviano, close to Udine, on 
Monday [11 April] turned away a squadron of U.S. F-16's which 
were scheduled to land there. The technical bureau froze all 
contracts on servicing NATO aircraft. 
  Well informed sources say that this rejection of the U.S. 
fighter planes, which came from Germany, is the result of 
increasingly deteriorating relations between the Italian Air 
Force and NATO. 
  Aviano has for months been one of NATO's main bases from 
where air actions over the former Bosnia-Herzegovina were 
launched. 
  The two U.S. F-16's, which bombed Serb positions near 
Gorazde 
on Sunday, also came from this air base. 
  NATO warplanes on Sunday bombed Serb positions near Gorazde, 
a Moslem enclave ruled by the United Nations as a safe area 
which was set to be demilitarized last spring. In late March 
10,000 Moslems surged from this zone in a strong offensive on 
Serb territories. 
  After the failure of the Moslem offensive the Serbs launched 
a strong counterattack coming to several km away from the city. 

</TEXT>

