<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kliridhis on British `Intervention' at Security Council </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kliridhis on British `Intervention' at Security Council </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1104123494 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 0900 GMT 11 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1104123494 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] President Glavkos Kliridhis warned that the 
continuation of dialogue will not be productive unless the UN 
Security Council makes the necessary decisions. One of these 
decisions, he stressed, is the disarmament of Cyprus. President 
Kliridhis made his statement this morning at Larnaca Airport 
before leaving for Strasbourg, where he will address the Council 
of Europe's Parliamentary Assembly. 
  President Kliridhis was talking with regard to the backstage 
deliberations at the Security Council regarding the UN secretary 
general's report. With the intervention Of Britain, the 
president said, the first report prepared by the UN secretary 
general's representatives in Cyprus did not circulate 
officially. The second one, which was prepared later, did. But 
the president said the British side claimed it intervened so 
that no report would circulate for 15 days so as to give the 
Turkish side time to accept the documents. President Kliridhis 
revealed that the UN secretary general's report, which was not 
circulated, noted very clearly that the Turkish Cypriot side 
does not have the political will to find a solution. He said 
the report also noted that there was no progress on the 
substance of the Cyprus issue or the Butrus-Ghali ideas, because 
there was no political will from the Turkish side. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

