<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Italy &amp; Vatican City </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ciampi Rejects Bosnian Serb Protest Over Air Bases </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ciampi Rejects Bosnian Serb Protest Over Air Bases </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR1304074894 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 2004 GMT 12 
Apr 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1304074894 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Bosnia/Italy: Ciampi Rejects Bosnia </F>
Serb Protest"] 
  [Text] (ANSA) Rome, April 12 -- Premier Carlo Azeglio 
Ciampi said today he was aware of only one protest from Bosnian 
Serbs over the use of the Aviano Air Base in northern Italy for 
NATO air strikes on Bosnian Serb positions near the Muslim 
enclave of Gorazde and added, "but certainly it is a protest 
which Italy can only reject." 
  Talking to representatives of the foreign press gathered in 
the premier's office, Ciampi said, "Events in Bosnia in these 
days can do nothing other than confirm Italy in its position 
pursued up to the present, which provides for joint action to 
apply maximum pressure to bring peace to Bosnia and, more in 
general, to all ex-Yugoslavia." 
  After noting that the deployment of NATO warplanes at air 
bases on Italian territory represents the nation's greater 
contribution to this effort, the head of government said Italy 
provided this assistance "with an awareness of the importance, 
and also the risks, connected to certain positions and can only 
calmly maintain this position." 
  Earlier today, the Italian press reported that the Bosnian 
Serb leader, Radovan Karadzic, had threatened to make Italy "pay 
dearly for its complicity in the attack" with reference to the 
second raid carried out Monday by NATO planes flying out of the 
Aviano base. 

</TEXT>

