<H3> <TI>   Forza Italia Warns Andreatta on Slovenia, Croatia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Forza Italia Warns Andreatta on Slovenia, Croatia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR1204112794 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 2112 GMT 11 
Apr 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1204112794 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Forza Italia Warns Andreatta on </F>
Slovenia, Croatia"] 
  [Text] (ANSA) Fiuggi, April 11 -- Forza Italia members of 
parliament meeting here Monday [11 April] approved unanimously a 
motion warning Foreign Minister Beniamino Andreatta against 
making any formal decision at the April 20 European Union [EU] 
meeting to discuss membership applications by Slovenia and 
Croatia. Forza Italia MPs warned the Rome government "not to 
compromise the issue of EU membership to Slovenia and Croatia 
with any irreversible acts" at the Brussels meeting, referring 
to possible acceptance by this government of future membership 
for the two former Yugoslav republics on Italy's northeastern 
borders. 
  The motion gives a clearer indication of what the foreign 
policies of a future government under the Freedom Pole (Forza 
Italia, Northern League and National Alliance) may be with 
respect to the two neighboring republics. 
  Those borders and former Italian territory now belonging to 
Slovenia and Croatia, as well as the issue of rights for the 
Italian minorities there, are being cited by the neofascist 
National Alliance as reasons for vetoing EU membership. 
  Forza Italia MPs, as their allies, evidently fear that 
Andreatta on April 20 may commit future Italian governments to 
grant Slovenia and Croatia EU membership. 
  "This government that will be in charge for just a few more 
days, representing political balances that have been turned 
upside down by the popular elections, in recent weeks has taken 
decisions that may jeopardize irrevocably delicate issues that 
are often crucial for future developments," the Forza Italia 
motion claimed. 
  National Alliance wants to renegotiate three postwar 
treaties 
signed with former Yugoslavia and wants to negotiate special 
rights for Italians living in the two republics. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

