<H3> <TI>   Ciampi Claims Merits in Starting Economic Recovery </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ciampi Claims Merits in Starting Economic Recovery </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR0704114094 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 2201 GMT 6 
Apr 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR0704114094 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Ciampi Claims Merits in Starting </F>
Economy on New Path"] 
  [Text] (ANSA) Rome, April 6 -- Italian Prime Minister Carlo 
Azeglio Ciampi, who moved from his job as governor of the Bank 
of Italy to take over the country's helm just under a year ago, 
voiced his "pride" here this evening for having made a 
successful and not just economic contribution to putting the 
country to rights. 
  In an interview with RAI-Uno, the public broadcasting 
corporation's flagship channel, to be broadcast tomorrow 
evening, he recalled that, when he came to power, he had 
promised to manage a situation "of great dangers" including a 
"giant public debt" using only ordinary means. 
  According to Ciampi, people were dubious about trying to 
manage the crisis through market means, but the results were 
falling interest rates and the re-conquered confidence of the 
international markets. He also said the key was the incomes 
policy agreement achieved with the unions last July 23. 
  Another major factor was the lira's devaluation, which had 
turned a balance-of-payments deficit of 30 trillion lire into a 
surplus of 15 trillion. 
  According to Ciampi, all this may mean that Italy may be the 
first European nation to plunge into a "real economic recovery." 
  He also cited his government's continuation of the battle 
against organised crime, its moves to uproot corruption and 
other forms of malfeasance from public and business life, and 
the measures laying the foundations for giving jobs to the young 
people. 
  In other points, he looked back fifty years to the 
Liberation 
in 1944. 
  "Anyone who saw Italy with their own eyes then can only say 
that the country has made enormous progress," he said. 
"Particularly in the early years, there was an ability for 
translating political ideals of liberty and justice into 
reality. There was an ability for conjugating the Catholic with 
the nonconfessional matrix." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

