<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   EU Takes Greece to Court Over FYROM Embargo </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    EU Takes Greece to Court Over FYROM Embargo </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1304102994 Paris AFP in English 1014 GMT 13 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1304102994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Brussels, April 13 (AFP) -- The European Union [EU] 
announced here Wednesday [13 April] that it was taking Greece to 
the European Court of Justice (ECJ) in an attempt to overturn a 
Greek trade embargo of The Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia 
[FYROM]. 
  The announcement by the European Commission followed 
Greece's 
failure to lift the blockade, imposed on February 16, after the 
EU executive decided on April 6 to go to court unless the 
embargo was ended within a week. 
  It was the first time that the European Union has taken a 
member country to court over an action which a member claimed 
was a response to a security threat. 
  On February 16 Greece blocked all Macedonian trade through 
the northern Greek port of Salonika, which handles most of the 
Macedonia's imports and exports. 
  Athens maintains that Macedonia robbed its name from the 
neighbouring northern Greece province of Macedonia. 
  It says this, plus the use of an ancient Greek sun symbol in 
the Macedonian flag and a reference in its constitution to 
liberating enslaved Macedonia, implies territorial ambitions on 
the northern Greek province. 
  The Commission objected because it said the embargo blocked 
trade of other EU countries with Macedonia, and could not be 
justified on the grounds that Macedonian actions had created 
international tension and the threat of war. 
  The Commission is hoping that the ECJ will quickly issue a 
temporary order that Greece should lift the embargo pending the 
court's decision on its legality. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

