<H3> <TI>   Army Activities in Rwanda </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Army Activities in Rwanda </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1204171494 Brussels La Une Radio Network in French 1600 
GMT 12 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1204171494 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels La Une Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] In its daily briefing in Brussels the Army spoke to 
the press, so, Annie Nameus, you have some extra details on the 
confused situation in Rwanda: 
  [Nameus] First, about the evacuation of Belgian nationals: 
troops have been to the south, in the direction of Nyamata, 
bringing back the Belgians who wanted to come, but some decided 
to stay, because the situation appears a little calmer in the 
south. This convoy is now back in Kigali. It didn't meet many 
obstacles, just a few roadblocks. 
  Another convoy also went out today, 20 km to the west of 
Kigali, and, in the northwest, some 20 people, mostly Belgians, 
were taken from Ruhengeri to Gisenyi, where they arrived in the 
middle of the afternoon, under escort by soldiers involved in 
military technical cooperation. 
  I should also report that there are about 30 people at 
Kigali 
airport; they arrived after the last C-130s had left. The 
evacuation of Belgian nationals from Kigali is not yet over, and 
no final date for the evacuation has yet been fixed. 
  It is now the second commando battalion that is responsible 
for the town of Kigali. They are now being called the second 
commando battalion and no longer UN peacekeeping troops. These 
troops are, so to say, putting on their green berets again under 
their blue helmets. 
  The airport and the interior of the country are now the 
responsibility of the intervention units. 

</TEXT>

