<H3> <TI>   Denies Anti-Belgian Drive </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Denies Anti-Belgian Drive </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1204173794 Brussels La Une Radio Network in French 1600 
GMT 12 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1204173794 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels La Une Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Passages within quotation marks recorded] </F>
  [Text] The Rwandan ambassador in Brussels [Francois 
Ngarukiyintwali] gave a press conference at noon today. The 
ambassador heard from the journalists that his government had 
fled from the capital, Kigali. Earlier, the ambassador denied 
that there is an anti-Belgian campaign in Kigali. Francoise 
Walminck, was that only a rumor? 
  [Ngarukiyintwali] "It is a rumor. I believe that, for Latin 
scholars, it would be necessary to find the etymology of the 
word in order to know what it means." 
  [Walminck] For weeks, Radio Mille Collines, a radio station 
close to the authorities, has been broadcasting anti-Belgian 
propaganda messages. 
  [Ngarukiyintwali] "And it is true that yesterday, I was 
summoned to the Foreign Ministry by Minister Claes's chef de 
cabinet. We spoke about various issues concerning the relations 
between Belgium and Rwanda." 
  [Walminck] But, for the ambassador: 
  [Ngarukiyintwali] "This anti-Belgian campaign in Rwanda does 
not exist." 
  [Walminck] Worse, the Rwandan Government is accusing the UN 
Mission in Rwanda and the UN soldiers of not exercising proper 
control at the airport when the attack on the presidential plane 
took place, and, even worse, of giving technical support to the 
Rwandan Patriotic Front [RPF] rebels and of playing an active 
role during the RPF operations against the Rwandan Army. 

</TEXT>

