<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Denktas Accuses UN of Altering Package </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Denktas Accuses UN of Altering Package </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1204171494 Nicosia Bayrak Radio in Turkish 1530 GMT 12 Apr 
94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1204171494 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Bayrak Radio </F>
<F P=105>  Turkish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] President Rauf Denktas has said that the UN 
Secretariat General has significantly altered the first package, 
which it claimed could not be changed, in favor of the Greek 
Cypriots. 
  Denktas assessed the statement Joe Clark, UN special envoy 
to 
Cyprus, made to reporters in New York. Denktas said that the 
benefits and rights promised to the Turkish Cypriot side in the 
first package have not yet been fulfilled, adding that the 
Turkish Cypriot side has been told that if it hands over Maras 
[Varosha] some of these promises will be kept. He said: This 
is most unreliable. Pointing out that the promises made to the 
Turkish Cypriot side should be kept, Denktas added that the 
changes made against the Turkish Cypriot side are not just 
details but substantial issues. He further pointed out that the 
promises made have been rescinded. Noting that the southern 
entrance to Maras should be kept under Turkish Cypriot control, 
Denktas said that this is an issue of vital importance for the 
Turkish Cypriots. He added that the UN secretary general's 
promise concerning this issue is not remembered by anyone but 
the Turkish Cypriot side. Pointing out that promises made on 
the Lefkosa [Nicosia] airport have also not been kept, Denktas 
said that this disrupts the equality but that no one seems to 
care. 
  Denktas reiterated that the Turkish Cypriot side is in favor 
of continuing the proximity talks, adding that the talks have 
been ended because of Greek Cypriot leader Kliridhis. He said: 
We are continuing our contacts with the UN officials. We will 
see what will happen in four weeks. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

