<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Arsenis: Greek Crews Will Not Fly NATO Planes </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Arsenis: Greek Crews Will Not Fly NATO Planes </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1204131194 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1237 GMT 12 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1204131194 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Athens, April 12 (TANJUG) -- Greek Defence Minister 
Yerasimos Arsenis said Tuesday [12 April] that Greek crews, 
objecting to NATO air strikes on Bosnian Serb positions near 
Gorazde, would no longer fly NATO AWACS planes. 
  Following a general staff meeting which has been in session 
overnight, Arsenis said that Greece would withdraw its only 
warship from the Adriatic if NATO marines became engaged in NATO 
actions against Bosnian Serbs. 
  He said that AWACS planes were not flying out of the NATO 
base in Aktio in northwestern Greece and that they had all been 
transferred to the NATO base in Aviano, Italy. 
  On April 10-11, NATO warplanes launched air strikes on 
Bosnian Serb positions near Gorazde, after Serb forces had 
crushed a Moslem offensive, mounted in early March from the 
"safe area" of Gorazde, which should have been demilitarized 
last spring. 
  However, Greek opposition parties found Greece's 
disassociation with the NATO action against Bosnian Serbs as 
insufficient and urged the government, despite Greece's NATO 
membership, to intervene promptly to avert the flaring up of the 
Bosnian conflict. 
  The United Left, the Communist Party of Greece and the 
Political Spring party said there was no justification for the 
NATO attack on Bosnian Serbs and added that it only served to 
the intrests of the West. 
  A conservative, New Democracy Party leader Miltiadis Evert 
late on Monday urged that Greece, currently holding the rotating 
presidency of the European Union (E.U.), should interfere with 
the European allies to help stop NATO actions in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

