<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Signs Air Transportation Accord </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Signs Air Transportation Accord </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1204170294 Ankara TRT Television Network in Turkish 1500 
GMT 12 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1204170294 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TRT Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Turkish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over video] </F>
  [Text] The official talks between Turkey and Croatia were 
held in Ankara today. An air transportation agreement was 
signed between the two countries. 
  Mate Granic, Croatian deputy prime minister and foreign 
minister who arrived in Ankara this morning, called on Foreign 
Minister Hikmet Cetin and conferred with him for some time. 
Later, talks were held between delegations headed by the 
foreign ministers of the two countries. 
  In a statement before the meeting, Cetin noted that there 
are 
historical ties between Turkey and Croatia and expressed the 
belief that economic and political relations will develop even 
further. Cetin remarked that the Serbs should also take part in 
the Washington agreement signed between Bosnians and Croatians. 
The Washington agreement is important in creating a 
multinational and multicultural Bosnia-Herzegovina, Cetin 
stressed. Expressing gratitude for Croatia's assistance to 
Turkish troop participation in the peace force in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, Cetin declared that Turkish soldiers will go 
to Bosnia-Herzegovina in order to contribute to peace. 
  In turn, Granic thanked Turkey for its contribution to the 
peace process. Explaining that the Washington agreement is 
important because it grants equal rights to Muslims and 
Croatians, Granic said: It is our aim to get the Serbs to also 
take part in this agreement. 
  Later, Turkey and Croatia signed an air transportation 
agreement. The agreement was signed by Ambassador Tugay 
Ulucevik, deputy under secretary of the Foreign Ministry, and 
Croatian Ambassador to Ankara (Hidayet Vichdivic). The 
agreement envisages bilateral cooperation in the field of civil 
aviation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

