<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cetin Comments on Agreements </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Cetin Comments on Agreements </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1204193494 Ankara TRT Television Network in Turkish 1700 
GMT 12 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1204193494 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TRT Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Turkish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over video] </F>
  [Excerpt] [Passage omitted] In a statement after the 
official Turkish-Croatian talks in Ankara today, Foreign 
Minister Hikmet Cetin said that the situation in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina and the Balkans was discussed at the talks. 
Announcing that Turkey's contribution will continue for the 
implementation of the Croatian-Bosnian agreement signed in 
Washington, Cetin remarked that agreement was reached to hold a 
meeting in Ankara with the participation of the foreign 
ministers of Bosnia-Herzegovina, Croatia, and Turkey in a bid to 
put the agreement into effect. He reported that the Turkish 
peace force to be sent to Bosnia-Herzegovina was also discussed 
with the Croatian delegation. 
  Cetin declared that agreements on the prevention of double 
taxation, promotion of investments, and economic cooperation 
will be signed as soon as possible with the aim of developing 
Turkish-Croatian relations. Cetin also stated that Turkey and 
Croatia will appoint military attaches to their respective 
embassies and Croatia will open a consulate general in Istanbul. 
Possibilities for bilateral cooperation in the field of defense 
industry will also be explored, Cetin noted, adding that the 
Croatian side welcomed Turkey's contribution on the rebuilding 
of the Mostar Bridge and other cultural works. Cetin announced 
that on 17 April, Croatian Airlines will begin Zagreb-Istanbul 
flights and ro-ro [roll-on/roll-off] connections will also be 
secured. 
  In his statement after the talks between the delegations, 
Mate Granic, Croatian deputy prime minister and foreign 
minister, said that the talks in Ankara were very successful. 
He expressed the belief that bilateral relations will develop 
further with each passing day. Granic remarked that the United 
States, Russia, and the European Union are exerting efforts to 
organize a meeting among the Croatians, Bosnians, and Serbs. 
  Granic was received by President Suleyman Demirel at the 
Cankaya Mansion this afternoon. The visiting minister will 
leave Turkey tomorrow. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

