<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   UNHCR To Deliver Aid to Refugees in Southern Rwanda </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UNHCR To Deliver Aid to Refugees in Southern Rwanda </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1204145594 Paris AFP in English 1441 GMT 12 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1204145594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Geneva, April 12 (AFP) -- The United Nations High 
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) has been authorised to take 
aid to some 267,000 Burundian refugees in camps in southern 
Rwanda, UNHCR spokeswoman Sylvana Foa said Tuesday [12 April]. 
  Foa also said that close to 10,000 other people, fleeing the 
violence in Rwanda, were seeking refuge in the region. 
  Some 8,100 refugees had just arrived in Zaire, Foa said, 
adding that the information was still incomplete. Among these, 
she said, there were 5,000 Burundians who feared an explosion of 
violence in their country, 2,000 Rwandans and 1,100 Burundian 
refugees from Rwanda. 
  Foa said the UNHCR had not seen the kind of exodus from 
Rwanda it feared might occur, perhaps because people were afraid 
to move. 
  The Burundian prime minister had given the UNHCR permission 
to cross the border between Burundi and Rwanda to take supplies 
to the Burundian refugees, Foa added. 

</TEXT>

