<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   NATO `Ready' To Launch More Air Strikes in Bosnia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    NATO `Ready' To Launch More Air Strikes in Bosnia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1304133894 Paris AFP in English 1315 GMT 13 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1304133894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Brussels, April 13 (AFP) -- The North Atlantic 
Treaty Organisation (NATO) is ready to launch new air strikes in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina if United Nations forces are endangered in 
attacks there, a NATO spokesman said here Wednesday [13 April]. 
  Speaking after a meeting of ambassadors from NATO countries, 
he said they had expressed "general satisfaction" at two attacks 
by U.S. warplanes on Serb positions around the Bosnian Moslem 
enclave of Gorazde on Sunday and Monday. 
  "General satisfaction was expressed at the two missions 
conducted under the authority of Resolution 836 of the UN 
Security Council according to permanent procedures fixed with 
the UN Protection Force in Bosnia last year," he said. 
  Resolution 836 provides for the protection of "safe areas," 
including Sarajevo, Gorazde and four more towns, which have 
predominantly Moslem populations. 
  "NATO remains ready to provide close air support in case of 
new attacks against UNPROFOR (UN Protection Force) in the 
accomplishment of its global mandate," the spokesman said. 

</TEXT>

