<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   EU Ministers Agree To Tighten Fish Import Controls </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    EU Ministers Agree To Tighten Fish Import Controls </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1204172994 Paris AFP in English 1711 GMT 12 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1204172994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Luxembourg, April 12 (AFP) -- European Union [EU] 
fisheries ministers agreed here Tuesday [12 April] to apply 
stricter controls on fish imports, mainly from Russian, 
Ukrainian and Polish ships, in a bid to combat a glut of cheap 
foreign fish. 
  A majority of countries overruled objections from Britain, 
Denmark and the Netherlands that tighter controls were 
protectionist and unnecessary. 
  The new regulations, due to come into effect on May 15, 
provide that the fish from foreign boats can be off-loaded only 
at designated ports where they can be subjected to EU health and 
veterinary controls. 
  The imported fish will also have to be sold at prices which 
do not under-cut minimum levels set each year by the EU or by 
producer organisations at the port of entry. The new rules do 
not apply to fish imports for processing plants. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

