<F P=100> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   CDU Readiness for UN in Bosnia `Growing' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    CDU Readiness for UN in Bosnia `Growing' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1304134894 Munich SUEDDEUTSCHE ZEITUNG in German 13 Apr 94 
p 4 </F>

<F P=103> AU1304134894 </F>
<F P=104>  Munich SUEDDEUTSCHE ZEITUNG </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["eli"-signed report: "Growing Readiness for Bundeswehr </F>
Missions"] 
  [Text] Readiness is growing within the Christian 
Democratic Union [CDU] to allow the participation of the 
Bundeswehr in UN peacekeeping missions in the former Yugoslavia. 
At the same time, leading CDU politicians have been trying to 
put the statement by Chancellor Helmut Kohl that German ground 
troops must not be deployed in the Balkans because of the 
historical burden in proper perspective. One day before the 
arrival of UN Secretary General Butrus Butrus-Ghali in Bonn, the 
CDU presidium discussed the war in Bosnia. Considerations 
apparently also played a role that the debate on the 
participation in UN operations might lead to a clear 
delimitation vis-a-vis the Social Democratic Party of Germany 
[SPD] during the election campaign. 
  After CDU/Christian Social Union [CSU] Bundestag group 
leader 
and deputy chairman Karl-Heinz Hornhues, Defense Minister Volker 
Ruehe, too, seems to have adopted a different attitude on this 
issue. In an interview that was distributed at the Defense 
Ministry, Ruehe stated: "If a peace plan were to be 
implemented, we should be able to go to the limits of our 
capacities." 
  In the past, Ruehe spoke only vaguely about a commitment on 
the fringes of the conflict zone -- at NATO airports in Italy, 
for example, and by establishing a field hospital in Croatia. 
He now only excluded participation in operations in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. In the interview, he stated: "German 
soldiers in Bosnia-Herzegovina would rather be part of the 
problem and not of a solution because their commitment and their 
work would not be supported by all parties to the conflict. 
Thus, the deployment of German soldiers there is not 
realistic." Defense Ministry officials have pointed out that, 
with his statements, Ruehe has increased the range of 
possibilities. It would be conceivable for pioneers to 
participate in the reconstruction of the country and for 
transport troops to resupply the UN troop. However, German 
soldiers will not monitor peace with weapons in their hands as 
long as the Constitutional Court does not pass a ruling on the 
deployment of Bundeswehr soldiers outside the NATO area. 
  Bundestag group chairman Schaeuble stressed two weeks ago 
during a visit to Washington that, "basically," the government 
will participate in a UN mission to safeguard peace in the 
Balkans. NATO cannot sustain a peacekeeping mission if Germany 
refuses to participate, he added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

